An American-style favoritism capitalism
Do you remember the East Asian crisis? When the U.S. Treasury Department and its IMF allies shifted the blame for the region's problems onto a favoritism-based capitalism, a lack of transparency, and an ineffective government?
The countries were encouraged to follow the American model, to use American accounting firms, and to bring in American entrepreneurs to teach them how to run their businesses.
It doesn't matter that under the leadership of its own entrepreneurs, East Asia has developed more rapidly than any other region - and with greater stability - over the last three decades.
The growing Enron scandal gives new meaning to two well-known American proverbs: "You reap what you sow" and "You must be flawless to criticize others."
Enron used large accounting tricks and complicated financial products (derivatives) to mislead investors about its value.
No transparency here.
She used her money to gain influence and power, shape U.S. energy policy, and avoid regulations.
Favoritism-based capitalism is not new, nor is it the exclusive domain of a single party.
The former U.S. Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, is said to have attempted to influence the current government to intervene on Enron's behalf in the controversial conflict in India.
When in office, he intervened when the supposedly independent accounting standards-setting body attempted to clean up the accounting of executive-related lucrative deals.
It is partly due to him that this effort to make corporate accounting more transparent was hindered.
The enthusiasm of America to bail out airlines with several billion dollars or to create cartels to protect its steel and aluminum industries suggests that the ideology of free markets is merely a thin veil for the benefit of established businesses: giving to those with the right connections.
For some, the fact that Enron was not bailed out and that the problems were not revealed testifies to the absence of favoritism-based capitalism.
My interpretation is different: it testifies to the importance of a free press that may not stop abuses but can reduce them.
When the press began to look into Enron, the number of members of Congress who had accepted money from Enron was revealed.
Campaign contributions were not simply a matter of public interest, but constituted an investment.
Like most of Enron's investments, everything went smoothly in the short term, but did not yield results in the long term.
Several lessons can be drawn from this company.
Some concerning politics: the Enron scandal reinforces arguments in favor of campaign finance reform and the need for even more effective laws that must be made public.
Democracies are undermined by corporate interests capable of actually buying elections.
The Bush administration, however, refuses to disclose information that would attest to the role of corporate interests in shaping its energy policy.
Other lessons pertain to economics, more specifically to the economics of information.
For markets to function, for the appropriate signals aiming to allocate resources efficiently to be provided, investors must receive as much information as possible.
There are inherent conflicts of interest: owners and managers are naturally motivated to present as positive a picture as possible.
Accounting oversight is intended to set limits on potential abuses.
But who will watch the watchers?
Who will watch the accountants?
We rely heavily on motivations.
The auditors wish to preserve their reputation.
But the relationship between advisory practices and accounting oversight brings about other perverted motivations: a motivation to please clients who do not appreciate unfavorable reports.
Arthur Levitt, the former chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, acknowledged the conflict: given that many within accounting firms focus on their own short-term interests, the integrity of oversight could be compromised.
He is undoubtedly the unrecognized hero of the debacle.
But accounting firms and their corporate clients - which comes as no surprise, given the cabal that has developed - have strongly attacked his proposal to separate advisory and accounting oversight activities.
What Levitt understood—and that the Enron debacle so clearly demonstrated—is that motivations are important, but unimpeded markets cannot by themselves provide the best motivations.
Markets cannot provide motivations for the creation of wealth; they can provide motivations for the type of schemes that Enron was implementing.
The new economy—and its complex new financial instruments—highlight the problems of reliable accounting control structures; they make them easier to manipulate.
Rather than confronting the problems, American-style corporate America systematically turns its back on them, supported and encouraged by American-style favoritism capitalism.
The major problem of our era is to find the right balance between government and the market.
The status quo will argue that Enron is an exception: that its collapse was due to fraud, that we have laws against fraud, and that those who violate these laws must suffer the consequences and will suffer them.
But the majority of Enron's actions were legal.
Its auditors declare that its core practices complied with the law and that thousands of companies act in the same way.
They are right - and that is precisely the problem.
Investors need to be sure that the information received sufficiently reflects a company's economic situation.
Under the current regulatory and legal framework, with derivatives and other off-balance-sheet liabilities, investors currently have no possibility of being offered these guarantees.
We need better standards and more effective laws.
Although we will never be able to prevent all abuses, we can check the motivations.
We can attempt to instill better ethical standards.
But we cannot rely on them when so many people in the world find nothing wrong with the phenomenon of the "revolving door".
They claim to manage conflicts of interest, but we observe that they can manage them for their own interests.
But even when evidence of this type of abuse becomes evident, new places for abuse are created repeatedly - take the American repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act, which separated commercial from investments.
We have repeatedly observed the consequences of the excesses of unimpeded market liberation.
We must now resist the temptation to lean toward the other extreme.
The challenge to be met is to achieve the right balance.
